            "new_string": "## 7. Implementation Plan: Single PR, 5 Commits\n\nOne PR against `feat/lan-discovery` with each fix as its own commit. Run full checks after each commit.\n\n**Verification after each commit:**\n```bash\ncargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets\ncargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings\ncargo fmt --all -- --check\n```\n\n---\n\n### Commit 1: `fix: exempt identity endpoint from Basic Auth`\n\n**File:** `apps/node/src/api.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Lines 87-98 — the `/api/v1/identity` route is merged into the router *before* the `check_basic_auth` middleware layer is applied at line 94. But Axum layers wrap everything above them, so the identity endpoint IS behind auth. LAN discovery peers without credentials will get 401.\n\n**Fix:** Split the router into public and authenticated sections:\n\n```rust\n// Public routes (no auth required)\nlet public_routes = Router::new()\n    .route(\"/api/v1/identity\", get(get_identity))\n    .route(\"/api/v1/health\", get(health_check));\n\n// Authenticated routes\nlet auth_routes = Router::new()\n    .merge(submit_route)\n    .merge(fetch_route)\n    .route(\"/api/v1/stats\", get(get_stats))\n    .layer(DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_BODY_SIZE))\n    .layer(middleware::from_fn_with_state(state.clone(), check_basic_auth));\n\n// Combine\nRouter::new()\n    .merge(public_routes)\n    .merge(auth_routes)\n    .with_state(state)\n```\n\nNote: `health_check` should also be public (monitoring probes shouldn't need auth). `DefaultBodyLimit` stays on auth_routes since identity/health have no body.\n\n**Test:** Existing identity endpoint tests in `apps/node/tests/identity_endpoint.rs` should still pass. Add a test that verifies identity endpoint works when auth is configured.\n\n---\n\n### Commit 2: `fix: cap identity response body size`\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Line 340 — `resp.content_length().unwrap_or(0)` returns 0 when `Content-Length` header is absent, bypassing the size guard. A malicious peer can omit the header and send an arbitrarily large body.\n\n**Fix:** Read bytes first, then check size:\n\n```rust\n// Replace lines 339-345:\nlet bytes = resp.bytes().await?;\nif bytes.len() as u64 > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES {\n    debug!(\"Identity response too large ({} bytes), skipping\", bytes.len());\n    return Ok(None);\n}\n\nlet body: IdentityResponse = serde_json::from_slice(&bytes)\n    .map_err(|e| {\n        debug!(\"Failed to parse identity response: {e}\");\n    })\n    .ok()\n    .map_or_else(|| Ok(None), |b| Ok(Some(b)))?;\n```\n\nActually simpler — just replace the `resp.json()` call:\n\n```rust\nlet bytes = resp.bytes().await?;\nif bytes.len() as u64 > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES {\n    debug!(\"Identity response too large ({} bytes), skipping\", bytes.len());\n    return Ok(None);\n}\nlet Ok(body) = serde_json::from_slice::<IdentityResponse>(&bytes) else {\n    return Ok(None);\n};\n```\n\nThis requires adding `serde_json` to `apps/client/Cargo.toml` (or it may already be there transitively). Check before adding.\n\n---\n\n### Commit 3: `fix: remove dead conditional in handle_update`\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Lines 274-278 — the early return at 274 guarantees that the condition at 278 is always true.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the outer `if` at line 278, dedent the block:\n\n```rust\nfn handle_update(...) {\n    let entry = self.peer_index.get(instance_name)\n        .expect(\"invariant: is_update implies entry exists\");\n    let address_changed = entry.url != url;\n    let identity_changed = entry.verified_identity != verified;\n    let old_target_id = entry.target_id.clone();\n\n    if !address_changed && !identity_changed {\n        return;\n    }\n\n    // Build and replace target (always reaches here)\n    let Some(target) = Self::build_http_target(instance_name, url, verified) else {\n        return;\n    };\n    coordinator.replace_http_target(&old_target_id, target);\n\n    if address_changed {\n        info!(instance = %instance_name, old_url = %entry.url, new_url = %url,\n              \"Updated discovered peer address\");\n    } else {\n        info!(instance = %instance_name, \"Updated discovered peer identity\");\n    }\n\n    self.peer_index.insert(\n        instance_name.to_owned(),\n        PeerEntry {\n            target_id: TargetId::http(url),\n            verified_identity: verified,\n            url: url.to_owned(),\n        },\n    );\n}\n```\n\nAlso fix the update short-circuit at line 158 to compare against stored URL:\n\n```rust\n// Line 158: was comparing addresses[0], should compare stored url\nif is_update {\n    let entry = &self.peer_index[&peer.instance_name];\n    // Check if ANY new address matches the stored URL\n    let any_match = peer.addresses.iter().any(|&addr| {\n        let candidate = format!(\"http://{}\", SocketAddr::new(addr, peer.port));\n        entry.url == candidate\n    });\n    if any_match {\n        debug!(instance = %peer.instance_name,\n               \"Update with matching address, skipping re-verification\");\n        return;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Commit 4: `refactor: feature-gate fake discovery backend`\n\n**Files:** `crates/reme-discovery/src/lib.rs`, `crates/reme-discovery/Cargo.toml`\n\n**Problem:** `pub mod fake` ships in production builds. Only used by crate-internal tests.\n\n**Fix:**\n\nIn `Cargo.toml`, add a `test-utils` feature:\n```toml\n[features]\nmdns-sd = [\"dep:mdns-sd\", \"dep:hostname\"]\ntest-utils = []\n```\n\nIn `lib.rs`:\n```rust\n#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]\npub mod fake;\n```\n\nNo downstream crates import `reme_discovery::fake`, so no other changes needed. Verify with `cargo build -p reme-discovery` (without `--all-features`).\n\n---\n\n### Commit 5: `fix: emit PeerUpdated for re-resolved mDNS services`\n\n**Files:** `crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs`, `crates/reme-discovery/src/fake.rs`\n\n**Problem:** `Service